{{Infobox website | name=LearnHub | screenshot= LearnhubScreenshot homepage.png | owner=Savvica Inc. | type=Social Learning Network | launched=March 2008 | url = {{URL|learnhub.com}} }}
'''LearnHub''' was a [[Social learning (social pedagogy)|social learning]] network for [[study abroad|international education]]<ref>{{cite web| publisher=Indian Express| title=International Degree Programs| url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/now-apply-for-int-degree-programs-through-learnhub/420085/2| date=February 6, 2009| accessdate=June 18, 2010}}</ref> run by Savvica Inc.,<ref>{{cite web| publisher=The Telegraph| title=Ticket to Fly| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090416/jsp/careergraph/story_10820799.jsp| date=April 16, 2009| accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref> an online learning company based in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=LearnHub Profile| publisher=Industry Canada| url=http://www.ic.gc.ca/app/ccc/srch/nvgt.do?lang=eng&prtl=1&sbPrtl=&estblmntNo=234567090059&profile=cmpltPrfl&profileId=1861&app=sold| date=March 2010| accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> The website was launched in 2008 to help [[Indian students abroad|Indian students]] find [[higher education]] opportunities primarily in the US, the UK and Canada. The website was shut down in 2013 following closure of the company's Toronto headquarters. The site offered test preparation tools, a university program directory, student counselling and a career network.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Hindustan Times | title= Learnhub.com dons a new look |url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/Learnhub-com-dons-a-new-look-launches-Learnhub-2-0/Article1-540562.aspx| date= May 7, 2010| accessdate= June 18, 2010}}</ref> In May 2010, LearnHub became the 30th most visited website in India.<ref>{{cite web| title=Quantcast| url=http://www.quantcast.com/| accessdate=June 21, 2010}}</ref> In June 2011 Learnhub was 13th most visited site in India<ref>{{cite web|title=Quantcast|url=http://www.quantcast.com/learnhub.com | accessdate=June 20, 2011}}</ref> and the most popular education website in India. This success was highly cyclical and was a result of the traffic spikes in May/June when Indian students were using the vast free test prep database housed on the site. As of December 2012, LearnHub closed its Toronto office and stopped updating its website, Twitter and Facebook pages, suggesting that the company was no longer operating. In April 2013, [[Top Hat Monocle]] announced that LearnHub co-founder and former CEO Malgosia Green became the company's new Chief Product Officer.<ref>http://www.techvibes.com/blog/top-hat-monocle-adds-two-new-executives-ralf-riekers-and-malgosia-green-2013-04-18</ref>
==Social learning network== LearnHub was a social learning network which used [[Web 2.0]] to allow international students to form discussions concerning higher education and studying abroad.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/torontos-transformation-to-silicon-valley-north/article1593023/| publisher=Globe and Mail| last=Tossel| first=Ivor|title=Toronto's Transformation to Silicon Valley North| date=June 4, 2010| accessdate=June 21, 2010}}</ref> It was designed to allow people to share learning and knowledge in online communities.<ref>{{cite news| last=Pain| first=Paromita| title=Learn Together| newspaper=The Hindu| location=Delhi| date=June 30, 2008| url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/ednahubfellow/2627393563/sizes/o/| accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref>
==Test preparation== LearnHub offered free access to [[Indian Institute of Technology Joint Entrance Examination|IIT-JEE]], [[Birla Institute of Technology and Science|BITSAT]], [[All India Engineering Entrance Examination|AIEEE]], [[SAT Reasoning Test|SAT]], [[Graduate Management Admission Test|GMAT]], [[Graduate Record Examination|GRE]] and [[Test of English as a Foreign Language|TOEFL]] practice exams and question banks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hindustan Times| publisher=Hindustan Times}}</ref> The site included thousands of original practice test questions.<ref>{{cite news| publisher=The Education Times| location=India| title=Question Banks| date=July 14, 2008|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/ednahubfellow/2670664949/|accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref> Students could also check the government released results of IIT JEE on the website.<ref>{{cite web| publisher=Spot this Now |title=IIT JEE Results 2010 Available at JEE.learnhub.com| url=http://www.spotthisnow.com/2010/05/iit-jee-results-2010-available-at-jee-learnhub-com/| date=May 26, 2010| accessdate=June 21, 2010}}</ref>
==Program directory== LearnHub had a program directory with information about university and college programs from the UK, the US, Canada, India and South Korea. These programs could be filtered by destination country, subject and education level.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=Digital Learning | title=Indian Students to have access to international degree programmes through LearnHub.com | url=http://issuu.com/dl_magazine/docs/dl_march_2009_issue |date=March 2009 | accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref>
==University and college directory== LearnHub contained articles about universities and colleges. These articles contained information about the location, campus, academic programs, tuition and financial aid. LearnHub had partnered with a variety of institutions, including public and private Colleges and Universities, [[Technical Institute|technical institutes]], research institutions, and [[liberal arts college]]s.
